{"title_page": "Le Petit Parisien", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2014}}\n{{Infobox newspaper\n| name                = Le Petit Parisien\n| image               = Fuerte San Carlos 1902.jpg\n| caption             = Illustrated literary supplement, January 1903.\n| type                = Daily [[newspaper]]\n| format              = [[Broadsheet]]\n| foundation          = 1876\n| ceased publication  = 1944\n| owners              = \n| political position  = \n| publisher           = \n| editor              = \n| staff               = \n| circulation         = 2,000,000+ <1920s> Daily\n| headquarters        = [[Paris]]\n| ISSN                = \n| website             = \n}}\n[[File:Frontpage French newspaper \"Le Petit Parisien\" Sepember 4 1939.jpg|thumb|Frontpage French newspaper \"Le Petit Parisien\" September 4 1939]]\n'''''Le Petit Parisien''''' was a prominent French newspaper during the [[French Third Republic]]. It was published between 1876 and 1944, and its circulation was over two million after the [[First World War]].\n\n==Publishing==\nDespite its name, the paper was circulated across France, and records showed claims that it had the biggest newspaper circulation in the world at this time.<ref>[http://www.archivesnationales.culture.gouv.fr/chan/chan/pdf/ARASAQ/11AR.pdf {{in lang|fr}} Fonds du Petit Parisien, [[Archives nationales (France)|Archives nationales]] (French national archives)] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060929074017/http://www.archivesnationales.culture.gouv.fr/chan/chan/pdf/ARASAQ/11AR.pdf |date=29 September 2006 }}</ref> In May 1927, the paper fell into a [[media prank]] set up by [[Jean-Paul Sartre]] and his friends, announcing that [[Charles Lindbergh]] was going to be awarded as ''[[\u00c9cole Normale Sup\u00e9rieure]]'' honorary student.<ref>Hayman, Ronald (1987) [https://books.google.com/books?id=eCpBAQAAIAAJ ''Sartre: a life''] pp.69, 318</ref> During the [[Second World War]] the paper, under the editorship of [[Claude Jeantet]], was the official voice of the [[Vichy regime]] and in 1944 was briefly published by Jeantet in [[Nazi Germany]] before closing down.<ref>[[Philip Rees]], ''[[Biographical Dictionary of the Extreme Right Since 1890]]'', 1990, p. 198</ref>\n\n==Background==\nPrior to the twentieth century, newspapers were largely political such as Paris's [[La Presse (French newspaper)|''La Presse'']]. This is largely because newspapers held close ties with political parties in order to profit. However, this led to a stunt in circulation. The creation of Joseph Pulitzer's newspaper [[Le Matin (France)|''Le Matin'']] inspired a new type of journalism. It prompted the start of [[Le Petit Journal (newspaper)|''Le Petit Journal'']] and ''Le Petit Parisien'' which launched French journalism into a mass medium. These newspapers offered sensationalized news rather than relying on political propaganda which also meant they avoided the tax held on most political newspapers. This new style, reporting on topics such as finance and fashion, targeted mid to lower class readers. Appealing to this demographic helped launch ''Le Petit Parisien''{{\u2019}}s circulation to the millions.<ref name=\"auto\">Eaman, Ross. ''Historical Dictionary of Journalism''. Scarecrow Press, 2009.</ref>\n\n==Illustration==\n''Le Petit Parisien'' featured a weekly, Sunday illustration located on their front pages. These illustrations were often visual representation of current events and paired with an article located within the newspaper. Because photography was not readily available, the newspaper relied on local artists to provide drawings and sketches for human interest stories. The purpose of these illustrated covers was to capture the eye of the passerby. Some illustrations are noted as risqu\u00e9 or scandalous, with the intentional use of getting the attention of readers.<ref>{{cite web|title=Women in Bed with Snakes and Other News. The Year 1900 in ''Le Petit Parisien\u2019s'' Illustrated Supplement - Poisonous Pens: Belle \u00c9poque Media Culture|publisher=poisonouspens.wordpress.com|accessdate= 8 September 2014|url=http://poisonouspens.wordpress.com/2014/05/08/women-in-bed-with-snakes-and-other-news/}}</ref> These covers are studied by many artists for their aesthetic appeal and many researchers for their impact on sales.\n\n==Writers==\nUp until the mid twentieth century, there was no formal school for journalism in Europe.<ref name=\"auto\"/> Therefore, the writers for ''Le Petit Parisien'' had no journalism education and were often activists and elite authors with many areas of expertise. Among the newspaper's guest writers was international correspondent [[Andr\u00e9e Viollis]].<ref>Brunazzi, Elizabeth. \"Andr\u00e9e Viollis: A \u2018Grand Reporter\u2019 in the Intellectual Resistance, 1942\u22121944.\" ''French Cultural Studies'' 22, no. 3 (1 August 2011): 229\u201337. {{doi|10.1177/0957155811408815}}.</ref>\n\n==Collapse==\nDuring the interwar years, the heavy swap of editors suggests that ''Le Petit Parisien'' was suffering the effects of unregulated media ownership that plagued France until the 1980s.<ref>Eaman, Ross. The A to Z of Journalism. Scarecrow Press, 2009.</ref> ''Le Petit Parisien'' did not survive its policy of collaboration with the [[Occupation of France by Nazi germany|German invaders]] during World War II, in spite of its efforts towards rehabilitation.\n\n==National Library of France\u2014Gallica==\nAll copies of ''Le Petit Parisien'' can be found at the National Library of France\u2014Gallica website.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/cb34419111x/date|title=Le Petit Parisien (Paris) - 69 ann\u00e9es disponibles - Gallica|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[History of French journalism]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category|Le Petit Parisien}}\n* Digitized issues of [http://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/cb34419111x/date ''Le Petit Parisien''] in [[Gallica]], the digital library of the [[BnF]]. {{in lang|fr}}\n* Digitized issues of [http://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/cb344191170/date suppl\u00e9ment litt\u00e9raire du ''Petit Parisien''] in [[Gallica]].{{in lang|fr}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Petit Parisien}}\n[[Category:1876 establishments in France]]\n[[Category:1944 disestablishments in France]]\n[[Category:Defunct newspapers of France]]\n[[Category:Publications established in 1876]]\n[[Category:Publications disestablished in 1944]]\n[[Category:Newspapers published in Paris]]\n[[Category:Newspapers of the Vichy regime]]\n[[Category:Daily newspapers published in France]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2014}}\n{{Infobox newspaper\n| name                = Le Petit Parisien\n| image               = Fuerte San Carlos 1902.jpg\n| caption             = Illustrated literary supplement, January 1903.\n| type                = Daily [[newspaper]]\n| format              = [[Broadsheet]]\n| foundation          = 1876\n| ceased publication  = 1944\n| owners              = \n| political position  = \n| publisher           = \n| editor              = \n| staff               = \n| circulation         = 2,000,000+ <1920s> Daily\n| headquarters        = [[Paris]]\n| ISSN                = \n| website             = \n}}\n[[File:Frontpage French newspaper \"Le Petit Parisien\" Sepember 4 1939.jpg|thumb|Frontpage French newspaper \"Le Petit Parisien\" Sepember 4 1939]]\n'''''Le Petit Parisien''''' was a prominent French newspaper during the [[French Third Republic]]. It was published between 1876 and 1944, and its circulation was over two million after the [[First World War]].\n\n==Publishing==\nDespite its name, the paper was circulated across France, and records showed claims that it had the biggest newspaper circulation in the world at this time.<ref>[http://www.archivesnationales.culture.gouv.fr/chan/chan/pdf/ARASAQ/11AR.pdf {{in lang|fr}} Fonds du Petit Parisien, [[Archives nationales (France)|Archives nationales]] (French national archives)] 